name: High-performance WAF built on the OpenResty stack
description:
lua-resty-waf is a reverse proxy WAF built using the OpenResty stack. It uses the Nginx Lua API to analyze HTTP request information and process against a flexible rule structure. lua-resty-waf is distributed with a ruleset that mimics the ModSecurity CRS, as well as a few custom rules built during initial development and testing, and a small virtual patchset for emerging threats. Additionally, lua-resty-waf is distributed with tooling to automatically translate existing ModSecurity rules, allowing users to extend lua-resty-waf implementation without the need to learn a new rule syntax.

lua-resty-waf was initially developed by Robert Paprocki for his Master's thesis at Western Governor's University.

A vibrant and active community for building embedded Linux.

For more info see: https://www.yoctoproject.org/sites/default/files/yp_backgrounder_shortfinal.pdf

For more info see: https://wiki.yoctoproject.org/wiki/Bugzilla_Configuration_and_Bug_Tracking
contribution_justification: http://openembedded.org/wiki/Commit_Patch_Message_Guidelines

The MIT license is widely acknowledged as being OSS. 
https://opensource.org/licenses
https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT
The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://www.yoctoproject.org/documentation
repo_public_justification: The Yocto project is using git: https://git.yoctoproject.org/cgit/cgit.cgi/poky/
repo_distributed_justification: We use git (https://git.yoctoproject.org)
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: https://wiki.yoctoproject.org/wiki/Security (See "How to Contact Yocto's security team Securely")
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: The Yocto Project Security team have two contact person for private secure communication.
build_justification:
The Yocto Project is using Buildbot for the continuous integration services.
yocto-builds@yoctoproject.org
https://autobuilder.yoctoproject.org/main/builders
build_common_tools_justification:
The Yocto Project is using bitbake. 
BitBake is a make-like build tool with the special focus of distributions and packages for embedded Linux cross compilation although it is not limited to that.
test_invocation_justification: We have many forms of automated testing which conform to standards where possible (e.g. python unittest). See our testing manual: http://docs.yoctoproject.org/test-manual/index.html
test_policy_justification:
The project has many different automated testing methods such as bitbake-selftest, oe-selftest, runtime image testing under qemu, SDK testing under qemu. More details are available at: https://www.yoctoproject.org/docs/2.6/mega-manual/mega-manual.html#testing-and-quality-assurance 
We informally ask for tests for new functionality at this point but its something we're actively encouraging.
tests_are_added_justification: Tests are run before code merges, mid release and at release. The counts of these tests increases for each release demonstrating increasing test coverage.
warnings_justification: Our equivalent code is insane.bbclass which has warnings and errors mode for most of its tests. We also pass in various 'security' cflags and ldflags.
warnings_fixed_justification: We aim to handle all warnings/errors raised by our sanity tests and handle errors from our security cflags and ldflags
warnings_strict_justification: Where our autobuilder generates warnings, we flag and fix these so that our builds don't show them.
know_common_errors_justification:
Richard Purdie <richard.purdie@linuxfoundation.org>
Michael Halstead <michael@yoctoproject.org>
Sona Sarmadi <sona.sarmadi@enea.com>
See: https://wiki.yoctoproject.org/wiki/Security
crypto_pfs_justification: We follow upstream project best practices in our images
crypto_password_storage_justification: We follow upstream project best practices in our images
crypto_random_justification: We follow upstream project best practices in our images
delivery_mitm_justification: The project uses https or git.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: The master branch tracks upstream versions and applies any security fixes we're made aware that we need. Our stable branches are trickier but we have a policy of applying any reasonable security patches that are made available to us in a timely fashion.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: The bugzilla doesn't have any open critical vulnerabilities.
static_analysis_justification: We run pylint as part of our automated testing process (our codebase is primarily python based) with a view to improving our score over time
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: We use pylint since our codebase is python based
static_analysis_fixed_justification: Our security and  release processes mandate any security exploitable vulnerabilities be fixed in a timely way!
static_analysis_often_justification: We run it as part of our pre-merge batch patch testing (we're too big to run against every commit and that doesn't make sense for us)
dynamic_analysis_justification: The project uses many forms of testing  appropriate to a build system.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: As a build system we do not fuzz the upstream software we build, we consider that the job of the upstream developers and it would be impractical to do this for a whole Linux stack. Our main build tools and code base is primarily python based so its not memory-unsafe.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: The codebase does sanity check its state where it needs to and would warn/error as appropriate if conditions warranted it.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: Any medium and high severity exploitable vulnerabilities would be fixed as general policy, whether discovered with dynamic code analysis or not.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: Our default configurations use best known algorithms and update to match current best practises.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: We have extensive automated CI testing: https://autobuilder.yoctoproject.org/typhoon/#/console
discussion_justification:
Monthly thechnical meeting:
https://www.yoctoproject.org/tools-resources/community/monthly-technical-call

IRC channel:
https://www.yoctoproject.org/tools-resources/community/irc

Mailing lists:
https://lists.yoctoproject.org/pipermail/yocto/
hardening_justification: The project is a configurable build system and users can chose to include many different levels of hardening. By default we include compiler options, this can range through to selinux and other software from the meta-security layer http://git.yoctoproject.org/cgit.cgi/meta-security
crypto_used_network_justification: We prefer secure versions of networking components
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: We use TLS certificate verification by default
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: We believe software we're including does do this
hardened_site_justification: X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff". // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: We don't install/uninstall our software as we're primarily a build system. We do support package managers on our target images.
build_reproducible_justification: We require our builds to reproducible, test this and publish results: https://www.yoctoproject.org/reproducible-build-results/
governance_justification: The Yocto project has a full charter and governance model https://www.yoctoproject.org/about/governance/
access_continuity_justification: The Linux Foundation (https://linuxfoundation.org/) hosts the project, there are dedicated system administrators (plural) and Technical Steering Committees which would act to ensure continuity.
bus_factor_justification: We average over 25 different contributors per week: http://git.yoctoproject.org/cgit.cgi/poky/stats/?period=w&ofs=-1
documentation_current_justification: The project employs a tech writer to help with this too! https://www.yoctoproject.org/docs/
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: We aim to be as inclusive as possible and have no known accessibility issues with our documentation, website or tools.
internationalization_justification: The project is about development tools and isn't for end users
sites_password_security_justification: The project uses key identification for repository and download site purposes
maintenance_or_update_justification: We maintain stable release branches for a period of one year and provide upgrade paths to newer versions.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: No vulnerabilities resolved in the last 12 months
coding_standards_enforced_justification: Our recipe metadata format is our own and our tools error/warn if they find issues in the metadata. We run testing at patch submission time through patchtest/patchwork and on our autobuilder infrastructure before merging changes.
build_standard_variables_justification: As a cross compiling system we're acutely aware of handling compiler/linker flags correctly.
build_preserve_debug_justification: We allow the user to configure debug symbol handling
build_non_recursive_justification: We have advanced dependency handling and handle parallelism correctly
build_repeatable_justification: We have reproducibility testing and can demonstrate we can generate bit-for-bit identical results for the same input configuration
installation_standard_variables_justific: We make extensive use of DESTDIR
installation_development_quick_justifica: As a build system we offer the user the ability to make and test changes
external_dependencies_justification: Our documentation lists the requirements for common distributions we test/support http://docs.yoctoproject.org/brief-yoctoprojectqs/index.html
dependency_monitoring_justification: We regularly test on different distributions on our autobuilder infrastructure
interfaces_current_justification: We have minimal dependencies and don't use obsolete components
automated_integration_testing_justificat: We do pre commit testing on batches of patches pre-merge and that system produces extensive test reports
regression_tests_added50_justification: We are a build system building complete linux (and other OS) stacks so the breadth of our bug load makes this impractical. We can point out that we run around 2 million tests on any given autobuilder run including glibc and gcc test suites any one of which could trigger a bug report. We do have a policy of adding regression tests for the areas where bugs occur or could have significant impact.
test_statement_coverage80_justification: We use our own file format and a mix of python and shell which makes this metric inapplicable.
implement_secure_design_justification: The project works to appropriate best practices for the tasks it undertakes such as checksumming its input source code and licenses and implementing reproducibility
input_validation_justification: The project builds upstream source code but we checksum the code coming in, or verify it through version control systems so there is always a chain of checksums to verify the build system inputs.
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: The project uses components which support multiple algorithms and we can switch components easily too.
crypto_credential_agility_justification: We rely on the components we build and configure to do this but all of our default recipes follow this best practise.
signed_releases_justification: We sign the release tags in our repositories which are how we expect our users to primarily use the project
contributors_unassociated_justification: We have multiple contributors from multiple companies: http://git.yoctoproject.org/cgit.cgi/poky/stats/?period=w&ofs=-1
license_per_file_justification: We have  SPDX-License-Identifier lines in our source code
code_review_standards_justification: We have documentation about patch submission referred to in our README files in each repository and these point at documents like http://www.openembedded.org/wiki/How_to_submit_a_patch_to_OpenEmbedded
two_person_review_justification: All patches are posted on the mailing list and peer reviewed before testing and merging,
test_statement_coverage90_justification: We use our own metadata and languages so this isn't applicable
test_branch_coverage80_justification: We use our own metadata and languages so this isn't applicable
security_review_justification: The project TSC has discussed and revised the project's security actions within the last 5 years and made many improvements such as the automated and frequency CVE scans which can be seen on the yocto-security mailing list,
assurance_case_justification: As a configurable OS build tool this is tricky but the project is world leading used by many different companies in different environments and we encourage collaboration on any issues encountered and sharing and collaborating around best practises. We have processes for managing and verifying build reproducibility, building and running security and audit tools and regularly run CVE scans for components with known issues amongst other things. As such, common security weaknesses would be identified, raised with is and rectified. https://wiki.yoctoproject.org/wiki/Security https://wiki.yoctoproject.org/wiki/Reproducible_Builds
